WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.714 --> 00:00:07.341
[stove burner clicking. ignites]

2
00:00:08.007 --> 00:00:09.218
[egg cracks]

3
00:00:14.973 --> 00:00:15.974
[sizzling]

4
00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:47.881
Mm-hmm.

5
00:00:47.965 --> 00:00:49.675
-Morning.
-Morning.

6
00:00:57.558 --> 00:00:58.892
[clears throat]

7
00:01:00.435 --> 00:01:01.520
What's this?

8
00:01:01.979 --> 00:01:03.981
It's just some paperwork for you to sign.

9
00:01:11.572 --> 00:01:14.741
What? You're canceling our cruise
to the Bahamas?

10
00:01:14.825 --> 00:01:17.619
If you're going back to space.
it doesn't make much sense. does it?

11
00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:20.539
-Wait. what?
-So which mission is it gonna be?

12
00:01:21.206 --> 00:01:23.959
You've already been to the moon.
so that's out of the question.

13
00:01:24.042 --> 00:01:26.628
And Skylab. you know. is doing good work.

14
00:01:26.712 --> 00:01:29.381
but let's be honest.
it's far too boring for you.

15
00:01:29.464 --> 00:01:34.553
So I'm guessing
the first flight of <i>Pathfinder.</i> yeah?

16
00:01:35.554 --> 00:01:38.015
I mean. you know.
it's cutting-edge technology

17
00:01:38.098 --> 00:01:40.225
filled with stuff that can malfunction.

18
00:01:40.309 --> 00:01:42.060
It's a test pilot's dream.

19
00:01:45.439 --> 00:01:48.442
Karen. I'm not going back.
I'm perfectly happy--

20
00:01:48.525 --> 00:01:49.568
No. you're not. Ed.

21
00:01:50.402 --> 00:01:52.279
You made that very clear last night.

22
00:01:53.447 --> 00:01:54.656
What are you talking about?

23
00:01:54.740 --> 00:01:56.742
You said you made a promise to yourself

24
00:01:56.825 --> 00:01:59.161
that you would never
leave me and Kelly alone.

25
00:01:59.244 --> 00:02:01.580
no matter what you had to give up.

26
00:02:03.665 --> 00:02:07.711
Come on.
I was very upset. and I overreacted.

27
00:02:07.794 --> 00:02:09.630
And you said exactly what you feel.

28
00:02:12.257 --> 00:02:15.177
-What I meant was--
-I know what you meant. Ed.

29
00:02:18.055 --> 00:02:20.807
It's not just... that.

30
00:02:25.103 --> 00:02:27.564
You don't think I notice
the look in your eyes at every launch.

31
00:02:28.982 --> 00:02:30.651
Or when you talk about <i>Pathfinder.</i>

32
00:02:42.829 --> 00:02:44.373
We raised a wonderful daughter.

33
00:02:46.583 --> 00:02:49.628
And you've been there for her
every step of the way.

34
00:02:52.005 --> 00:02:54.049
And now she's going off
to live her dreams.

35
00:02:54.132 --> 00:02:56.134
and there's no reason
that you shouldn't too.

36
00:03:00.973 --> 00:03:02.599
I won't put you through that again.

37
00:03:02.683 --> 00:03:03.684
I can handle it.

38
00:03:08.397 --> 00:03:11.817
But you should know.
it's gonna be different this time.

39
00:03:13.277 --> 00:03:15.863
You know. I have a business to run.

40
00:03:16.989 --> 00:03:20.367
So I can't sit by a squawk box all day
and night wondering if you're okay.

41
00:03:21.535 --> 00:03:23.287
It's not that I don't support you.

42
00:03:24.079 --> 00:03:25.664
I do.

43
00:03:25.747 --> 00:03:28.333
I can't get sucked into all of that again.

44
00:03:29.793 --> 00:03:30.794
I c-- I can't.

45
00:03:33.922 --> 00:03:34.923
Then...

46
00:03:36.175 --> 00:03:37.384
I shouldn't go.

47
00:03:37.467 --> 00:03:38.468
Yes. you should.

48
00:03:41.221 --> 00:03:43.765
Do you really think you can
sit behind a desk from 8:00 to 6:00

49
00:03:43.849 --> 00:03:45.809
for another 15 years?

50
00:03:53.275 --> 00:03:55.777
Y-- You really think--

51
00:03:55.861 --> 00:03:58.197
Yes. I do.

52
00:04:05.204 --> 00:04:06.371
I said I can handle it.

53
00:04:07.289 --> 00:04:08.290
And I will.

54
00:04:59.466 --> 00:05:00.968
["Working for the Weekend" plays]

55
00:05:22.865 --> 00:05:24.199
[song fades]

56
00:06:26.386 --> 00:06:28.597
<i>Sometimes you just gotta stop
wringing your hands...</i>

57
00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:31.934
and fly. or nothing gets done.

58
00:06:33.602 --> 00:06:34.811
[woman] Roger that. Gordo.

59
00:06:35.771 --> 00:06:38.065
It's refreshing
to have you back in the saddle.

60
00:06:38.148 --> 00:06:39.149
It's good to be back.

61
00:06:39.691 --> 00:06:43.195
-I miss you hard chargers. Test pilots.
-[chuckles]

62
00:06:43.278 --> 00:06:45.697
Yeah. we like to push everything
to the fire wall. all right.

63
00:06:45.781 --> 00:06:46.782
Amen.

64
00:06:46.865 --> 00:06:48.784
[radio chatter]

65
00:06:50.244 --> 00:06:52.079
You good with this suit. Gordo?

66
00:06:52.162 --> 00:06:55.999
If not. we could put you
into one of the old A7LB's.

67
00:06:56.083 --> 00:06:57.084
I like it.

68
00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:00.212
Can raise my hands a lot higher.

69
00:07:01.129 --> 00:07:05.259
Gotta say though.
don't much like this turtle shell.

70
00:07:05.342 --> 00:07:07.010
Durability comes with a price.

71
00:07:07.094 --> 00:07:08.512
But be sure you're comfortable.

72
00:07:08.595 --> 00:07:10.430
You'll be spending a lot of time
in one of these.

73
00:07:10.514 --> 00:07:13.100
Loving every minute. thinking of you.

74
00:07:13.183 --> 00:07:14.685
You never give up. do you?

75
00:07:15.018 --> 00:07:17.312
-Charm looms large in my legend.
-[chuckles]

76
00:07:18.313 --> 00:07:19.356
[clicks]

77
00:07:19.982 --> 00:07:22.651
Just the brain bucket
and you're ready to rock.

78
00:07:22.734 --> 00:07:23.735
About time.

79
00:07:39.418 --> 00:07:40.419
You okay? All good?

80
00:07:41.753 --> 00:07:44.548
-[breathing heavily]
-[heartbeat thumping]

81
00:07:51.305 --> 00:07:54.766
[uneven breathing]

82
00:07:58.520 --> 00:07:59.855
I can't hear you.

83
00:08:03.066 --> 00:08:05.110
[heartbeat pounding]

84
00:08:05.194 --> 00:08:06.278
Comm's on.

85
00:08:07.029 --> 00:08:08.655
Gordo. are you okay in there?

86
00:08:09.239 --> 00:08:10.282
Yeah. I'm good.

87
00:08:11.366 --> 00:08:12.826
Comm's cut out.

88
00:08:20.751 --> 00:08:22.503
[sighs]

89
00:08:23.253 --> 00:08:25.589
-You look a little flushed.
-Yeah. it's kinda hot in there.

90
00:08:25.672 --> 00:08:28.133
We'll swap out the CCA
and get you rolling inside ten minutes.

91
00:08:28.217 --> 00:08:29.426
That's a no go.

92
00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:31.762
Might have to scrub this for today.

93
00:08:31.845 --> 00:08:34.222
I just remembered
I'm due over at building 9.

94
00:08:34.306 --> 00:08:36.683
I gotta take a leak.
and I'm not gonna use the damn MAG.

95
00:08:38.644 --> 00:08:42.731
[panting]

96
00:08:54.368 --> 00:08:57.663
[deep breaths. whimpers]

97
00:09:00.707 --> 00:09:03.085
I'm telling you. Dan. keep an eye on her.

98
00:09:03.168 --> 00:09:05.254
I know Annapolis
has changed and everything.

99
00:09:05.337 --> 00:09:07.005
but it hasn't changed that much.

100
00:09:07.506 --> 00:09:11.593
Don't let any of those midshipmen
razz my daughter. okay?

101
00:09:12.094 --> 00:09:13.262
Aye. aye. sir.

102
00:09:14.930 --> 00:09:17.015
Hey. hey! Where you going with that?

103
00:09:19.810 --> 00:09:21.311
-Hi. Bob.
-[Dani] Hi. Bob.

104
00:09:21.395 --> 00:09:22.396
Hi. Bob!

105
00:09:23.438 --> 00:09:24.439
Grab a glass.

106
00:09:27.568 --> 00:09:28.735
What are we celebrating?

107
00:09:29.736 --> 00:09:31.238
Well...

108
00:09:31.321 --> 00:09:35.075
two old-timers managed to finish first
and second on their proficiency tests.

109
00:09:35.158 --> 00:09:36.618
I will drink to that.

110
00:09:42.374 --> 00:09:43.709
Y'all did good.

111
00:09:43.792 --> 00:09:46.128
Waxed the tails
of those pimply-faced rookies.

112
00:09:46.211 --> 00:09:47.212
[chuckles]

113
00:09:47.296 --> 00:09:48.297
Expected nothing less.

114
00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:50.799
Okay. now what are we drinking to
this time?

115
00:09:51.842 --> 00:09:56.305
Someone we all know and love
and deeply admire.

116
00:09:56.388 --> 00:09:58.056
One of the greatest.

117
00:09:58.140 --> 00:10:01.393
if... not the greatest astronaut
of our time

118
00:10:01.476 --> 00:10:04.605
has decided to return to space
and command <i>Pathfinder.</i>

119
00:10:04.688 --> 00:10:06.648
Oh. Neil Armstrong.

120
00:10:06.732 --> 00:10:08.317
Mm-mmm. mm-mmm. Frank Sedgewick.

121
00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:11.195
-Fuck y'all. I'm going back.
-[laughing]

122
00:10:11.278 --> 00:10:13.071
We heard. We heard.

123
00:10:13.155 --> 00:10:15.032
Yeah. word travels fast.

124
00:10:15.115 --> 00:10:19.453
Hey. I thought. uh. you didn't miss it
and you had no desire to go back?

125
00:10:20.287 --> 00:10:22.748
-You inspired me.
-Mm-hmm.

126
00:10:22.831 --> 00:10:24.833
So. you gave yourself <i>Pathfinder.</i>

127
00:10:25.834 --> 00:10:27.085
Must be nice to be king.

128
00:10:27.169 --> 00:10:32.007
What can I say? I got an eye
for spotting talent. like with you guys.

129
00:10:33.175 --> 00:10:35.385
I meant what I said. Y'all did great.

130
00:10:35.802 --> 00:10:38.472
I mean. that's a bit of a challenge.

131
00:10:38.972 --> 00:10:41.934
After all those years.
just jump right back into the deep end

132
00:10:42.017 --> 00:10:44.728
and making it look easy.

133
00:10:44.811 --> 00:10:46.021
[Dani chuckles]

134
00:10:47.147 --> 00:10:48.941
-[Ed] It's impressive.
-[chuckles]

135
00:10:52.027 --> 00:10:53.111
You okay. Gordo?

136
00:10:54.446 --> 00:10:55.447
Yeah.

137
00:10:58.075 --> 00:10:59.409
Something I should know about?

138
00:10:59.493 --> 00:11:00.494
No.

139
00:11:03.247 --> 00:11:04.248
Okay.

140
00:11:05.916 --> 00:11:08.001
I mean-- It's just...

141
00:11:09.628 --> 00:11:12.840
I had a weird little moment
in my suit today.

142
00:11:15.217 --> 00:11:17.344
-Weird moment? Where?
-[Dani] Like what?

143
00:11:17.719 --> 00:11:19.388
It was nothing. It was just...

144
00:11:20.764 --> 00:11:24.101
I felt trapped and short of breath and...

145
00:11:24.184 --> 00:11:25.269
[Dani] Mm-hmm.

146
00:11:25.352 --> 00:11:26.353
...I had to...

147
00:11:30.148 --> 00:11:31.191
Mmm.

148
00:11:31.275 --> 00:11:32.693
I had to take my helmet off.

149
00:11:38.490 --> 00:11:40.033
-Yeah.
-Did you tell anybody else about this?

150
00:11:40.117 --> 00:11:41.118
Course not.

151
00:11:46.456 --> 00:11:49.334
You didn't... see anything?

152
00:11:49.418 --> 00:11:51.128
Oh. no. No. it was nothing like that.

153
00:11:51.211 --> 00:11:54.840
Trust me. it's just. you know.

154
00:11:55.382 --> 00:11:57.176
like I said. felt a little hemmed in.

155
00:11:57.259 --> 00:11:58.594
-Oh.
-Yeah.

156
00:12:02.848 --> 00:12:06.935
Look. [chuckles] what happened up there
was nine years ago.

157
00:12:07.019 --> 00:12:09.521
-Mmm.
-You're not that guy.

158
00:12:09.605 --> 00:12:11.440
-I know.
-You're a different person now.

159
00:12:11.523 --> 00:12:14.026
And you've been to therapy.
You've dealt with your issues.

160
00:12:14.109 --> 00:12:15.360
Oh. yeah. I know.

161
00:12:15.444 --> 00:12:18.363
You finally cut the cord with Tracy.

162
00:12:18.447 --> 00:12:21.992
I mean. you're on the upswing. buddy.
You're-- You're getting your mojo back!

163
00:12:22.075 --> 00:12:24.077
I am. I haven't felt this good in years.

164
00:12:24.161 --> 00:12:26.205
-It was just a moment. is all.
-Yeah.

165
00:12:26.288 --> 00:12:27.289
No biggie.

166
00:12:27.706 --> 00:12:29.666
-Good. Good. Glad to hear it.
-No biggie.

167
00:12:31.877 --> 00:12:32.920
[sighs]

168
00:12:33.003 --> 00:12:35.214
[patrons chattering. laughing]

169
00:12:38.634 --> 00:12:39.801
[Ed] How you holding up?

170
00:12:41.178 --> 00:12:43.889
[Dani] Fine. Feels good to be back.

171
00:12:45.432 --> 00:12:49.269
Uh. I gotta go to Dallas
to see Clayton's sister tomorrow.

172
00:12:49.978 --> 00:12:51.480
take care of some family business.

173
00:12:51.563 --> 00:12:53.065
Really not looking forward to it.

174
00:12:53.565 --> 00:12:54.816
All right.

175
00:12:55.400 --> 00:12:58.987
So. Ed. now that you are stepping out...

176
00:12:59.947 --> 00:13:01.949
who's taking over the Astronaut Office?

177
00:13:02.032 --> 00:13:03.325
["I'm a Ramblin' Man" plays]

178
00:13:03.408 --> 00:13:04.493
[chuckles]

179
00:13:04.576 --> 00:13:05.702
[song continues]

180
00:13:07.788 --> 00:13:09.665
-[knocking]
-[door opens]

181
00:13:10.249 --> 00:13:11.250
[Ed] Molly?

182
00:13:12.501 --> 00:13:14.086
Ed? Is that you?

183
00:13:14.169 --> 00:13:15.170
Yep.

184
00:13:15.587 --> 00:13:16.922
Come on in. I'm in here.

185
00:13:21.510 --> 00:13:24.263
[song continues]

186
00:13:24.346 --> 00:13:25.389
[exhales]

187
00:13:25.472 --> 00:13:27.057
[chuckles]

188
00:13:27.933 --> 00:13:30.310
You always leave the door open
while you're bathing alone?

189
00:13:30.394 --> 00:13:31.728
Who says I'm alone?

190
00:13:33.230 --> 00:13:37.401
Golly gee.
Visitation from the chief astronaut.

191
00:13:37.484 --> 00:13:39.027
To what do I owe this honor?

192
00:13:39.111 --> 00:13:43.657
You missed our golf game again.
so I thought I'd check in.

193
00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:47.494
Right. You wanna get a beer
before you drop the other shoe. or...

194
00:13:51.123 --> 00:13:54.501
No. I'm just... Well. a beer is fine.

195
00:13:58.505 --> 00:13:59.756
[groans]

196
00:14:01.466 --> 00:14:05.262
Forgive me for not getting up.
Gravity's a bitch.

197
00:14:07.347 --> 00:14:08.974
[sighs]

198
00:14:10.809 --> 00:14:15.564
I'm. uh. here to put you back to work.

199
00:14:16.064 --> 00:14:18.817
This wild. happy. free life
has got to stop.

200
00:14:22.279 --> 00:14:25.449
Why do I think I am not gonna like this?

201
00:14:25.532 --> 00:14:27.284
-Because you know me.
-Uh-huh.

202
00:14:28.410 --> 00:14:30.454
I want you to run the Astronaut Office.

203
00:14:31.955 --> 00:14:33.165
[scoffs. chuckles]

204
00:14:33.248 --> 00:14:36.126
Me run the Astronaut Office.
What the hell for?

205
00:14:36.210 --> 00:14:38.921
Well. someone just put me
in command of <i>Pathfinder.</i>

206
00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:40.964
Oh. wow.

207
00:14:41.924 --> 00:14:46.345
You just assigned yourself the command
of the E ticket ride of the decade.

208
00:14:48.555 --> 00:14:50.682
Yep. Just like you told me to.

209
00:14:50.766 --> 00:14:52.935
Jesus Christ.
You weren't supposed to listen to me.

210
00:14:53.018 --> 00:14:54.394
I was just messing with you.

211
00:14:54.478 --> 00:14:55.562
Well. you were right.

212
00:14:55.646 --> 00:14:59.525
And assigning your own missions
is one of the perks of the job.

213
00:15:01.902 --> 00:15:03.570
That's a pretty ballsy move. Ed.

214
00:15:04.738 --> 00:15:06.156
You've never flown a shuttle.

215
00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:08.283
Mmm. No one's flown <i>Pathfinder.</i>

216
00:15:09.326 --> 00:15:13.372
Looks to me like you just handed yourself
a golden opportunity to screw the pooch.

217
00:15:13.455 --> 00:15:15.541
Always the optimist.

218
00:15:17.042 --> 00:15:18.043
So what do you say?

219
00:15:18.377 --> 00:15:21.880
I say no to that crown of thorns.

220
00:15:21.964 --> 00:15:24.591
Look. don't overlook the upside.

221
00:15:25.092 --> 00:15:26.760
Homage from favor seekers.

222
00:15:26.844 --> 00:15:30.264
Opportunities to wreak vengeance
on people who cross you.

223
00:15:33.934 --> 00:15:35.811
-Well. that sounds fun.
-Mm-hmm.

224
00:15:35.894 --> 00:15:37.771
But no. No.

225
00:15:39.314 --> 00:15:40.315
I just wanna fly.

226
00:15:40.399 --> 00:15:41.775
So. fly.

227
00:15:43.735 --> 00:15:47.197
You assign your own flights.
When your six-month medical hold ends...

228
00:15:47.823 --> 00:15:49.032
[clicks tongue]

229
00:15:51.451 --> 00:15:52.703
I pull a Baldwin?

230
00:15:53.537 --> 00:15:55.998
Put myself in the coolest thing flying?

231
00:16:00.752 --> 00:16:02.004
You bastard.

232
00:16:02.087 --> 00:16:03.297
[chuckles]

233
00:16:03.380 --> 00:16:06.133
You start in a week.
You can thank me later.

234
00:16:06.758 --> 00:16:10.137
A bottle of Glenfarclas 25 would be nice.

235
00:16:10.220 --> 00:16:12.222
Although Glenfiddich never disappoints.

236
00:16:19.229 --> 00:16:20.606
Molly Cobb...

237
00:16:22.107 --> 00:16:24.568
chief of the Astronaut Office.

238
00:16:31.491 --> 00:16:32.534
No way.

239
00:16:35.829 --> 00:16:37.831
I want you to know
I appreciated your call.

240
00:16:38.749 --> 00:16:41.084
We never got a chance to talk
at the funeral.

241
00:16:41.168 --> 00:16:43.587
-I wanted to--
-You said you have something for me.

242
00:16:45.464 --> 00:16:46.465
Yes.

243
00:16:48.133 --> 00:16:51.136
I finally worked up the nerve
to go through Clayton's closet.

244
00:16:51.762 --> 00:16:54.723
This was on the floor. shoved in the back.

245
00:16:55.766 --> 00:16:59.728
There are some personal items in here
I thought you might want.

246
00:17:02.898 --> 00:17:05.692
These are some of Clayton's report cards
from elementary school.

247
00:17:07.027 --> 00:17:08.237
[chuckles]

248
00:17:12.491 --> 00:17:16.703
These are some. uh. birthday cards
your mother wrote to him.

249
00:17:28.257 --> 00:17:29.842
Thank you for bringing me these.

250
00:17:36.223 --> 00:17:38.600
I know you and I
haven't always seen eye to eye.

251
00:17:39.518 --> 00:17:44.439
but I'm-- I'm hoping we can find a way
to make a fresh start.

252
00:17:46.984 --> 00:17:47.985
Why?

253
00:17:50.404 --> 00:17:52.114
Because we both loved Clayton.

254
00:17:53.866 --> 00:17:54.867
Uh-huh.

255
00:17:56.994 --> 00:17:58.412
What's that supposed to mean?

256
00:17:59.204 --> 00:18:03.166
I know you wanted him to admire you.
worship the ground you walked on.

257
00:18:03.250 --> 00:18:05.335
Is that what you call love?

258
00:18:05.419 --> 00:18:07.045
That's not at all what I--

259
00:18:09.423 --> 00:18:10.507
You don't know me.

260
00:18:11.884 --> 00:18:14.261
-You never bothered to.
-Oh. I know you. all right.

261
00:18:15.679 --> 00:18:18.056
Clayton told me
what really happened on the moon.

262
00:18:21.685 --> 00:18:22.686
What?

263
00:18:24.229 --> 00:18:26.273
-He wouldn't.
-He's never kept secrets from me.

264
00:18:27.608 --> 00:18:29.276
Told me how you really broke your arm.

265
00:18:31.862 --> 00:18:34.531
All to protect some white man's career.

266
00:18:34.615 --> 00:18:39.369
That man was my friend.
A part of my crew.

267
00:18:39.995 --> 00:18:41.705
The color of his skin
had nothing to do with it.

268
00:18:41.788 --> 00:18:45.542
And look how they've rewarded you.
Made you a laughingstock.

269
00:18:45.626 --> 00:18:48.337
If that were true. why would they send me
back to the moon?

270
00:18:50.005 --> 00:18:51.215
You're going again?

271
00:18:54.051 --> 00:18:55.260
Well. that's just great.

272
00:18:56.512 --> 00:18:58.347
You're gonna help them spend millions

273
00:18:58.430 --> 00:19:00.474
to find out if beans
will sprout on the moon.

274
00:19:00.557 --> 00:19:04.269
If they'd used that money to fund
a decent counseling program at the VA.

275
00:19:04.353 --> 00:19:06.104
maybe Clay wouldn't have killed himself.

276
00:19:08.815 --> 00:19:11.276
I don't know why I thought this time
would be any different.

277
00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:12.903
You are never gonna change.

278
00:19:14.780 --> 00:19:15.781
Hold on.

279
00:19:17.324 --> 00:19:18.825
I've got something for you too.

280
00:19:32.381 --> 00:19:33.465
This was Clay's?

281
00:19:38.345 --> 00:19:40.472
But he threw away all his medals.
I saw him do it.

282
00:19:40.556 --> 00:19:41.557
Not this one.

283
00:19:42.683 --> 00:19:44.309
-How did you--
-He gave it to me.

284
00:19:47.938 --> 00:19:49.022
I don't understand.

285
00:19:50.274 --> 00:19:51.608
Why are you giving this to me?

286
00:19:52.359 --> 00:19:55.237
You're the one who filled Clay's head
with all that patriotic crap.

287
00:19:56.905 --> 00:19:58.657
He joined the army because of you.

288
00:19:59.992 --> 00:20:01.910
He joined the army to serve his country.

289
00:20:02.327 --> 00:20:03.328
His country?

290
00:20:04.454 --> 00:20:06.290
He ever tell you
what his fellow soldiers did

291
00:20:06.373 --> 00:20:08.625
the day after Martin Luther King
was assassinated?

292
00:20:08.709 --> 00:20:09.918
They threw a party.

293
00:20:10.586 --> 00:20:14.214
Put on Klan outfits.
paraded around with Confederate flags.

294
00:20:15.215 --> 00:20:17.551
But. hey. they gave Clay a medal.
so that makes it all okay.

295
00:20:17.634 --> 00:20:21.263
-That wasn't the men in Clay's platoon.
-I'm not talking about his platoon.

296
00:20:21.930 --> 00:20:24.016
I'm talking about
the United States government.

297
00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:27.603
Uncle Sam used us as cannon fodder.

298
00:20:28.145 --> 00:20:30.272
Clayton was proud to serve.

299
00:20:30.355 --> 00:20:31.356
At first.

300
00:20:31.732 --> 00:20:35.819
But by the time he got back. he was just
putting on a good show to please you.

301
00:20:35.903 --> 00:20:38.572
He did everything for you.

302
00:20:38.655 --> 00:20:41.241
And now that's he's gone.
all you wanna do is forget him.

303
00:20:41.825 --> 00:20:42.826
Well. go ahead.

304
00:20:43.535 --> 00:20:46.413
Go back to the moon.
help them start another Vietnam up there.

305
00:20:46.496 --> 00:20:47.497
That is not--

306
00:20:48.665 --> 00:20:52.920
We are doing serious research
to build a better future for us all.

307
00:20:53.879 --> 00:20:55.380
You sound just like them.

308
00:20:56.632 --> 00:20:58.717
But you're not one of them. Never will be.

309
00:21:00.260 --> 00:21:03.847
They may have let you on the bus. but you
will always have to ride in the back.

310
00:21:14.525 --> 00:21:16.735
I know I've already brought this up...

311
00:21:18.320 --> 00:21:19.321
but...

312
00:21:20.322 --> 00:21:22.366
the moon was supposed to be
a stepping-stone.

313
00:21:22.449 --> 00:21:24.284
and it's become a quagmire.

314
00:21:24.368 --> 00:21:26.954
sucking up more and more
of our funding and resources--

315
00:21:27.037 --> 00:21:30.082
That's true. but the president doesn't
want the Soviets to gain the upper hand.

316
00:21:30.165 --> 00:21:31.250
Neither do I.

317
00:21:31.834 --> 00:21:34.962
If we put boots on the surface of Mars.
we'll have the ultimate upper hand.

318
00:21:38.590 --> 00:21:39.842
[sips]

319
00:21:39.925 --> 00:21:42.386
-What?
-You know what your problem is. Ellen?

320
00:21:43.971 --> 00:21:45.848
You're not fooling anyone.

321
00:21:50.561 --> 00:21:51.728
I. uh--

322
00:21:51.812 --> 00:21:53.105
Uh. what do you mean?

323
00:21:53.897 --> 00:21:56.066
You need to be a better poker player.

324
00:21:56.650 --> 00:21:58.235
You remember a couple years back

325
00:21:58.318 --> 00:22:01.154
when Senator Lang attacked
the cost overruns of our lunar program?

326
00:22:01.238 --> 00:22:02.865
Yeah. he called it a "moondoggle."

327
00:22:02.948 --> 00:22:04.324
Mm-hmm.

328
00:22:04.408 --> 00:22:05.909
I wrote that speech for him.

329
00:22:12.833 --> 00:22:14.042
Why would you do that?

330
00:22:14.126 --> 00:22:16.587
Lang was in the middle of
a tough reelection fight.

331
00:22:16.670 --> 00:22:17.838
Yeah. I remember.

332
00:22:18.422 --> 00:22:21.049
Coen accused him of being a pimp for NASA.

333
00:22:21.133 --> 00:22:23.677
And John needed to demonstrate
his independence.

334
00:22:25.012 --> 00:22:27.347
We already had more than enough votes
to pass the funding bill.

335
00:22:27.431 --> 00:22:29.057
so why not help him out?

336
00:22:29.474 --> 00:22:31.101
Then. after he won reelection--

337
00:22:31.185 --> 00:22:34.438
Lang turned around and sponsored the bill

338
00:22:34.521 --> 00:22:37.649
that allows NASA to license
its new technology to private industry.

339
00:22:37.733 --> 00:22:38.942
And because of that.

340
00:22:39.443 --> 00:22:43.113
this agency will be entirely self-funded
in less than ten years.

341
00:22:43.197 --> 00:22:45.407
Which will free us
from the whims of Congress.

342
00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:46.491
-[snaps fingers]
-Exactly.

343
00:22:47.159 --> 00:22:48.994
We'll have enough money to explore Mars.

344
00:22:49.745 --> 00:22:50.913
And we won't stop there.

345
00:22:51.413 --> 00:22:53.165
You and I will have a front row seat.

346
00:22:54.249 --> 00:22:56.502
As long as the Democrats
don't win next year.

347
00:22:56.585 --> 00:22:57.711
[Ellen chuckles]

348
00:23:00.797 --> 00:23:02.382
That must've been pretty difficult.

349
00:23:03.091 --> 00:23:04.593
Being at the center of everything.

350
00:23:04.676 --> 00:23:07.596
and then Teddy Kennedy wins
and you're out of a job.

351
00:23:07.679 --> 00:23:09.890
Just part of the game. The ups and downs.

352
00:23:11.475 --> 00:23:12.476
[Paine] Hmm.

353
00:23:12.559 --> 00:23:14.478
Was it Nixon who initially recruited you?

354
00:23:14.561 --> 00:23:15.812
[chuckles] No.

355
00:23:15.896 --> 00:23:19.608
No. no one recruited me.
I lobbied my ass off for this job.

356
00:23:22.861 --> 00:23:23.946
Really?

357
00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:27.866
Caught the bug when I was aboard
a submarine during the war.

358
00:23:31.286 --> 00:23:34.248
We'd surface at night
to recharge our batteries.

359
00:23:36.124 --> 00:23:37.626
Yeah. out there.

360
00:23:38.335 --> 00:23:42.339
alone in the Pacific.
the sky was packed with stars.

361
00:23:44.258 --> 00:23:47.386
We learned the names of quite a few
to navigate. but...

362
00:23:49.221 --> 00:23:51.098
I wanted to know them all.

363
00:23:51.181 --> 00:23:52.224
Hmm.

364
00:23:53.433 --> 00:23:56.979
After I got demobbed. I went out
and bought my first telescope...

365
00:23:58.313 --> 00:23:59.439
from the Sears catalog.

366
00:24:04.611 --> 00:24:06.613
-Shall I freshen you up?
-Sure.

367
00:24:12.244 --> 00:24:15.873
I didn't know you felt
so passionately about space.

368
00:24:19.543 --> 00:24:20.669
I guess I thought--

369
00:24:20.752 --> 00:24:23.297
What? That I'm a glad-handing politician

370
00:24:23.380 --> 00:24:25.924
who cares more about my career
than I do about NASA?

371
00:24:28.302 --> 00:24:30.804
Nah. it's okay. El.

372
00:24:30.888 --> 00:24:33.765
I know everyone at JSC
thinks I'm just Reagan's lackey.

373
00:24:34.224 --> 00:24:36.727
just like they thought I was
Nixon's lackey a decade ago.

374
00:24:36.810 --> 00:24:37.895
But I don't mind it.

375
00:24:39.897 --> 00:24:43.525
People have hated politicians as long as
there have been politicians. but...

376
00:24:45.152 --> 00:24:46.153
the truth is...

377
00:24:47.696 --> 00:24:49.698
we're the ones
that make this all possible.

378
00:24:52.618 --> 00:24:55.746
I wanna get to Mars as much as you do.
Believe me.

379
00:24:59.499 --> 00:25:01.585
You're gonna be a great asset to me.
Ellen.

380
00:25:02.669 --> 00:25:05.380
You're as genuine as the sunrise.

381
00:25:06.673 --> 00:25:08.008
People respond to that.

382
00:25:11.053 --> 00:25:13.055
Thank you. Tom. That's very kind.

383
00:25:13.555 --> 00:25:15.557
You'll get used to all the gamesmanship.

384
00:25:16.808 --> 00:25:18.435
We all play different roles
with different people.

385
00:25:18.519 --> 00:25:21.688
I'm a different Thomas Paine with Reagan
than I was with Nixon

386
00:25:21.772 --> 00:25:25.400
or Tip O'Neill or Margo Madison.

387
00:25:25.943 --> 00:25:29.530
And there's yet another me with my wife
when I go home at night.

388
00:25:36.537 --> 00:25:40.165
The trick is
not to lose track of who you really are.

389
00:25:46.463 --> 00:25:49.174
-[R & B plays]
-It's Scorsese's best picture.

390
00:25:49.258 --> 00:25:51.343
-You cannot be serious.
-It's a masterpiece.

391
00:25:51.426 --> 00:25:53.720
Oh. my. You're saying that
'cause you like Jerry Lewis.

392
00:25:53.804 --> 00:25:55.430
Well. what's-- what's not to like?

393
00:25:55.514 --> 00:25:56.515
Everything.

394
00:25:56.598 --> 00:25:57.933
[sighs]

395
00:25:58.392 --> 00:26:01.395
<i>The Nutty Professor</i>
is a brilliant indictment

396
00:26:01.895 --> 00:26:03.272
of the American male psyche.

397
00:26:03.355 --> 00:26:06.358
Okay. yours maybe.
I do not get this obsession at all.

398
00:26:06.441 --> 00:26:09.152
Says the guy who's seen <i>Yentl</i> 15 times.

399
00:26:09.236 --> 00:26:11.238
-That's so--
-Hey. El.

400
00:26:12.155 --> 00:26:13.407
How'd your day go?

401
00:26:13.490 --> 00:26:15.993
It was. uh. very interesting.

402
00:26:16.076 --> 00:26:19.496
Hey. we should [clicks tongue] go.
We don't wanna miss that first set.

403
00:26:21.248 --> 00:26:22.541
Where you guys off to?

404
00:26:22.624 --> 00:26:23.709
The Bullshot.

405
00:26:24.418 --> 00:26:27.921
They apparently have
a fantastic Donna Summer impersonator.

406
00:26:28.005 --> 00:26:29.006
Oh. [chuckles]

407
00:26:29.089 --> 00:26:30.340
-You should come with.
-Yeah.

408
00:26:30.424 --> 00:26:33.468
I'd love to.
but I have an 0800 meeting at JSC.

409
00:26:33.552 --> 00:26:35.971
Oh. you could stay for an hour.
then head home.

410
00:26:36.972 --> 00:26:39.433
You really should get out more.
have some fun.

411
00:26:39.516 --> 00:26:41.059
Yeah. come on.

412
00:26:41.143 --> 00:26:42.394
[chuckles]

413
00:26:42.895 --> 00:26:43.896
Another time.

414
00:26:43.979 --> 00:26:45.022
-Mmm.
-Ah.

415
00:26:45.105 --> 00:26:50.194
Okay. Well. if you're staying.
maybe you can go through your moon mail.

416
00:26:50.277 --> 00:26:52.571
You haven't touched it
since you've been back.

417
00:26:53.697 --> 00:26:54.907
[Ellen sighs]

418
00:26:54.990 --> 00:26:57.451
-Okay. Oh. my gosh.
-Mm-hmm.

419
00:26:57.534 --> 00:26:59.203
-Have fun.
-You too.

420
00:27:00.412 --> 00:27:01.747
That's a lot of mail.

421
00:27:02.372 --> 00:27:03.498
[Peter chuckles]

422
00:27:05.834 --> 00:27:07.503
[door closes]

423
00:28:57.571 --> 00:29:00.699
[CAPCOM] Discovery. <i>Launch Control.
We're gonna run abort check now.</i>

424
00:29:00.782 --> 00:29:01.783
[male astronaut] <i>Wilco.</i>

425
00:29:01.867 --> 00:29:03.285
Looks good. Control.

426
00:29:05.495 --> 00:29:09.291
[CAPCOM] <i>That brings us to the built-in
hold at T-minus nine minutes.</i>

427
00:29:09.374 --> 00:29:11.919
<i>Time for Tracy's big interview with NBC.</i>

428
00:29:12.002 --> 00:29:14.713
Starting to wonder
if we're just chauffeurs here.

429
00:29:15.881 --> 00:29:18.592
Think they left a makeup case
on the mid-deck if you wanna freshen up.

430
00:29:18.675 --> 00:29:20.636
-[astronaut 1 chuckles]
-Yeah. Very funny. y'all.

431
00:29:24.306 --> 00:29:26.433
Launch Control.
we have power to the Tracy cam.

432
00:29:27.434 --> 00:29:29.311
[CAPCOM]
<i>Roger.</i> Discovery. <i>Feed looks good.</i>

433
00:29:31.271 --> 00:29:35.317
<i>Okay. You're live in three. two. one.</i>

434
00:29:35.400 --> 00:29:37.319
-[beeps]
-Hey there.

435
00:29:37.903 --> 00:29:42.282
<i>Well. I am very happy to be talking to you
aboard the space shuttle</i> Discovery.

436
00:29:43.367 --> 00:29:46.495
<i>That's right.
I'm headed for six months on the moon.</i>

437
00:29:46.995 --> 00:29:48.539
<i>It's the trip of a lifetime.</i>

438
00:29:48.622 --> 00:29:51.625
<i>Only one regret. Sam and I
couldn't make it our honeymoon.</i>

439
00:29:52.292 --> 00:29:55.379
[Michaels] <i>A number of viewers have
asked why you're still using "Stevens"</i>

440
00:29:55.462 --> 00:29:57.631
<i>instead of your married name. "Cleveland."</i>

441
00:29:57.714 --> 00:29:58.799
<i>Care to tell us why?</i>

442
00:29:58.882 --> 00:30:02.135
<i>Well. you know.
everybody already knows me as Stevens.</i>

443
00:30:02.219 --> 00:30:03.971
<i>So. figured I'd stick with it.</i>

444
00:30:04.054 --> 00:30:05.764
<i>Save the taxpayers some money.</i>

445
00:30:06.348 --> 00:30:07.724
<i>I love you bunches. Sam.</i>

446
00:30:09.059 --> 00:30:12.229
[Michaels] <i>Astronaut Tracy Stevens.
speaking with us 40 minutes ago</i>

447
00:30:12.312 --> 00:30:15.440
<i>as she and her crew
made their final preparations for launch.</i>

448
00:30:16.108 --> 00:30:18.944
<i>I'm now being told the shuttle
is a mere two minutes from liftoff--</i>

449
00:30:19.027 --> 00:30:20.279
[applause. cheering]

450
00:30:20.362 --> 00:30:22.447
<i>Thank you. Thank you very much.</i>

451
00:30:22.531 --> 00:30:24.616
<i>Welcome to</i> Wheel of Fortune.
<i>Good to have you here.</i>

452
00:30:24.700 --> 00:30:28.495
<i>And now if you would do that one more time
for our hostess. Here comes Vanna White.</i>

453
00:30:28.579 --> 00:30:29.580
<i>Vanna.</i>

454
00:30:29.663 --> 00:30:30.789
[applause. cheering]

455
00:30:30.873 --> 00:30:31.874
<i>Hello.</i>

456
00:30:31.957 --> 00:30:34.793
<i>...only hope they don't get to our ships
before we do.</i>

457
00:30:38.422 --> 00:30:40.299
-[woman] <i>The air pressure's dropping.
-You're right.</i>

458
00:30:40.382 --> 00:30:42.509
[Sajak] <i>Father of two. You care to talk
about those two a little bit?</i>

459
00:30:42.593 --> 00:30:43.635
<i>Two fantastic kids.</i>

460
00:30:43.719 --> 00:30:46.805
<i>One under a year. still a baby. and then
a beautiful three-year-old daughter</i>

461
00:30:47.431 --> 00:30:49.141
<i>given to me by my gracious wife.</i>

462
00:30:49.224 --> 00:30:50.350
-[Sajak] <i>Well. it was...
-Two wonderful kids.</i>

463
00:30:50.434 --> 00:30:51.727
<i>...a fine thing of her to do.</i>

464
00:30:51.810 --> 00:30:53.729
<i>And it's nice to have you here. Jeff.
Wish you a lot of luck.</i>

465
00:30:53.812 --> 00:30:57.024
[man] <i>Eight. seven. six.</i>

466
00:30:57.107 --> 00:31:00.652
<i>Main engine start. Two. one--</i>

467
00:31:15.042 --> 00:31:16.168
So long. Trace.

468
00:31:22.299 --> 00:31:23.634
See you soon.

469
00:31:44.196 --> 00:31:45.822
What you got there. Mr. Piscotty?

470
00:31:46.532 --> 00:31:47.533
Oh. uh...

471
00:31:47.616 --> 00:31:49.409
Just a sandwich. sir.

472
00:31:50.827 --> 00:31:53.705
I hear it's your last day on the job.
Congratulations.

473
00:31:54.206 --> 00:31:55.415
Why don't you put that on.

474
00:31:59.378 --> 00:32:03.632
Uh. due respect. sir.
I'm air force. sir. not navy.

475
00:32:07.177 --> 00:32:08.220
Put it on.

476
00:32:19.523 --> 00:32:21.775
Now pull it down lower.

477
00:32:24.736 --> 00:32:25.821
Lower.

478
00:32:39.334 --> 00:32:40.627
That's gonna work.

479
00:32:42.671 --> 00:32:45.257
First of next week.
I want you to check out a T-38.

480
00:32:45.883 --> 00:32:46.884
meet me in Palmdale.

481
00:32:48.218 --> 00:32:50.554
Palmdale... California?

482
00:32:52.306 --> 00:32:53.557
Congratulations.

483
00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:56.351
You just drew right seat
of <i>Pathfinder's</i> maiden flight.

484
00:32:59.229 --> 00:33:00.272
Roger that. sir.

485
00:33:01.148 --> 00:33:02.149
Thank you.

486
00:33:27.090 --> 00:33:29.218
T-minus two hours and counting.

487
00:33:33.972 --> 00:33:35.516
-Hi. Bob.
-Hi. Bob.

488
00:33:35.974 --> 00:33:39.853
[sighs] Man. this place is gonna feel
so odd without you.

489
00:33:39.937 --> 00:33:41.146
[chuckles]

490
00:33:41.688 --> 00:33:43.315
I think I'm gonna leave this to Molly.

491
00:33:43.398 --> 00:33:46.151
Her short game sucks.
She could use the practice.

492
00:33:47.986 --> 00:33:49.238
I'm sure she'll love that.

493
00:33:51.657 --> 00:33:52.658
What's up?

494
00:33:58.121 --> 00:34:04.002
Ed. I want you to know that I appreciate
the assignment to Jamestown 91

495
00:34:04.086 --> 00:34:06.088
and that you came up with it so quickly.

496
00:34:06.171 --> 00:34:07.256
I really do.

497
00:34:08.632 --> 00:34:09.632
But...

498
00:34:11.592 --> 00:34:12.636
But what?

499
00:34:13.887 --> 00:34:14.972
It's not good enough.

500
00:34:18.266 --> 00:34:19.601
Not good enough?

501
00:34:19.685 --> 00:34:21.687
I'm sorry. but it's not.

502
00:34:24.022 --> 00:34:25.482
I want a command slot.

503
00:34:25.983 --> 00:34:28.652
Dani. you really have been out of the loop
for too long.

504
00:34:28.735 --> 00:34:30.821
You don't just waltz in and demand--

505
00:34:30.904 --> 00:34:33.072
You know the sacrifices I've made.

506
00:34:33.156 --> 00:34:34.658
How much time I've lost.

507
00:34:35.074 --> 00:34:37.619
I was the first African American
in space. Ed.

508
00:34:38.203 --> 00:34:40.746
And now here I am.
still riding in the back.

509
00:34:43.292 --> 00:34:44.293
Come on. Dani.

510
00:34:45.668 --> 00:34:47.170
You really gonna take it there?

511
00:34:47.254 --> 00:34:48.755
I've given it a lot of thought.

512
00:34:50.090 --> 00:34:54.094
I want to be the first African American
woman to command a mission.

513
00:34:54.511 --> 00:34:58.390
First woman Black commander
is now a thing?

514
00:34:58.473 --> 00:35:00.058
Seriously? We're gonna parse it that fine?

515
00:35:00.142 --> 00:35:02.144
You're damn right we are. Ed.

516
00:35:02.769 --> 00:35:04.771
If you don't give me a command spot.

517
00:35:04.855 --> 00:35:08.609
I will always be seen as that weak little
Black girl who fell apart on the moon.

518
00:35:08.692 --> 00:35:11.862
But if I were a white man.
they'd have forgiven me a long time ago.

519
00:35:11.945 --> 00:35:16.116
I understand it feels that way.
but it's just not true.

520
00:35:20.329 --> 00:35:24.291
Remember Mercury 4. when Gus Grissom
splashed and the hatch blew early?

521
00:35:24.374 --> 00:35:26.251
Press never let him forget about that.

522
00:35:26.335 --> 00:35:28.795
You know. that had nothing to do
with the color of his skin.

523
00:35:31.048 --> 00:35:33.967
Ed. how many astronauts do we have now?

524
00:35:36.553 --> 00:35:37.971
Two hundred and five.

525
00:35:39.306 --> 00:35:41.058
And how many of 'em are Black?

526
00:35:42.476 --> 00:35:43.602
Eleven.

527
00:35:43.685 --> 00:35:46.396
And how many of them
have commanded a mission?

528
00:35:49.816 --> 00:35:51.693
-One.
-Mm-hmm.

529
00:35:51.777 --> 00:35:54.821
Look. I hope you're not saying--
I hope you're not trying to imply that--

530
00:35:54.905 --> 00:35:57.032
I'm not trying to imply anything.

531
00:35:57.115 --> 00:35:58.742
I'm saying it straight.

532
00:35:59.326 --> 00:36:01.787
This is not good enough.

533
00:36:01.870 --> 00:36:04.706
Look. Dani. you gotta understand.
These things. they take time.

534
00:36:04.790 --> 00:36:08.585
You know. first they gotta qualify.
then they gotta be trained.

535
00:36:08.669 --> 00:36:10.754
and then they gotta get
some missions under their belt.

536
00:36:10.838 --> 00:36:12.840
Believe me. if they were ready.
they'd be commanding.

537
00:36:12.923 --> 00:36:16.301
"If they were ready"?
You sound like an NFL owner.

538
00:36:16.385 --> 00:36:18.679
Look. we've dealt with this issue.

539
00:36:18.762 --> 00:36:21.181
No. We haven't.

540
00:36:25.477 --> 00:36:29.022
Ed. I came into this program
as the token Black girl.

541
00:36:30.023 --> 00:36:33.277
And I was grateful for the opportunity.
no matter what the reasons.

542
00:36:34.027 --> 00:36:36.280
But that was 13 years ago.

543
00:36:36.780 --> 00:36:37.865
This program.

544
00:36:38.532 --> 00:36:42.244
it has the power to change the way
people see the world.

545
00:36:43.078 --> 00:36:44.162
You know that.

546
00:36:45.831 --> 00:36:48.166
I can't believe you're bringing this to me
on my last day.

547
00:36:48.250 --> 00:36:50.085
That's exactly why I'm bringing it up.

548
00:36:50.919 --> 00:36:52.754
Because until Molly takes over on Monday.

549
00:36:52.838 --> 00:36:55.299
you are the only one
with the power to do something.

550
00:36:58.927 --> 00:37:00.220
I gotta get to a meeting.

551
00:37:01.096 --> 00:37:02.222
[sighs]

552
00:37:12.524 --> 00:37:13.525
Sorry I'm late.

553
00:37:13.609 --> 00:37:14.610
[Bradford] Hey. hey.

554
00:37:15.068 --> 00:37:16.195
For you. Ed.

555
00:37:17.029 --> 00:37:20.991
In honor of your nine years of service
as head of the Astronaut Office.

556
00:37:24.286 --> 00:37:28.707
Am I supposed to make a wish?

557
00:37:29.041 --> 00:37:32.920
Hasn't it already been granted?
You're commanding <i>Pathfinder.</i>

558
00:37:33.003 --> 00:37:35.005
-[Bradford chuckles]
-[blows]

559
00:37:38.050 --> 00:37:39.259
What'd you wish for?

560
00:37:39.343 --> 00:37:40.928
To get on with this meeting.

561
00:37:41.470 --> 00:37:42.679
Amen to that.

562
00:37:42.930 --> 00:37:46.892
Uh. well. I have some exciting news.

563
00:37:47.267 --> 00:37:50.562
The. uh-- The Soviets have accepted
the president's offer

564
00:37:50.646 --> 00:37:54.149
to mount a joint mission
between our two space programs.

565
00:37:54.483 --> 00:37:56.276
You gotta be fucking kidding me.

566
00:37:57.152 --> 00:38:00.531
You said there was no chance
they would agree to this.

567
00:38:00.614 --> 00:38:03.992
Apparently Premier Andropov
is eager to demonstrate to the world

568
00:38:04.076 --> 00:38:08.330
that the Soviet Union has peaceful
intentions toward the United States.

569
00:38:08.413 --> 00:38:10.916
I've said it before.
This is complete bullshit.

570
00:38:11.250 --> 00:38:13.168
The Soviets are still flying Soyuz.

571
00:38:13.252 --> 00:38:15.963
Haven't even managed to get
their shuttle <i>Buran</i> off the ground.

572
00:38:16.046 --> 00:38:17.798
And the only reason
why they agreed to this

573
00:38:17.881 --> 00:38:20.592
is so they can get a closer look
at our current technology.

574
00:38:21.677 --> 00:38:23.053
We don't have to give it to them.

575
00:38:23.720 --> 00:38:26.265
We can show the Reds
only what they've already seen.

576
00:38:26.348 --> 00:38:27.349
Meaning?

577
00:38:27.432 --> 00:38:30.394
We have an old Apollo command module
in storage here at JSC.

578
00:38:30.477 --> 00:38:33.939
It was a backup rescue ship for Skylab
before shuttles took over that job.

579
00:38:34.022 --> 00:38:36.483
And we were gonna send it
to the Smithsonian.

580
00:38:36.567 --> 00:38:38.360
If we use an Apollo for this.

581
00:38:38.819 --> 00:38:41.488
the Russians won't get anywhere near
our shuttle systems.

582
00:38:42.447 --> 00:38:45.242
As long as we have
a Saturn 1B lying around as well.

583
00:38:46.034 --> 00:38:47.202
Huntsville's got one.

584
00:38:50.706 --> 00:38:51.790
Well. then it's doable.

585
00:38:52.332 --> 00:38:53.959
The president is gonna love this.

586
00:38:54.042 --> 00:38:57.462
He still talks about how heroic-looking
the old Apollos were.

587
00:38:58.088 --> 00:39:00.883
Right. well. the Soviets say
they're already picking a crew. so--

588
00:39:00.966 --> 00:39:03.260
To demonstrate
that they're fully committed.

589
00:39:03.343 --> 00:39:04.928
So we need to do the same.

590
00:39:06.346 --> 00:39:08.849
I hate to put pressure on you
on your last day. Ed.

591
00:39:08.932 --> 00:39:12.186
but I'm not sure I want to leave this
to Ms. Cobb.

592
00:39:12.644 --> 00:39:15.647
At least you'll only have to pick two now
after the modifications.

593
00:39:17.858 --> 00:39:19.610
I can give you the commander right now.

594
00:39:20.944 --> 00:39:23.614
I hope you're not
appointing yourself to this one too.

595
00:39:23.697 --> 00:39:26.450
Nope. I'm assigning Danielle Poole.

596
00:39:27.701 --> 00:39:31.038
She has extensive Apollo experience.
and she'll be perfect for this.

597
00:39:31.121 --> 00:39:32.122
Well. uh...

598
00:39:32.206 --> 00:39:35.417
Well. uh. we might want to consider
other possibilities.

599
00:39:37.044 --> 00:39:38.045
Why is that?

600
00:39:39.379 --> 00:39:42.299
Ed. this mission
is very important to the president.

601
00:39:42.382 --> 00:39:44.676
He wants
only the best of the best to fly it.

602
00:39:45.469 --> 00:39:47.721
I spent three months on the moon with her.

603
00:39:47.804 --> 00:39:50.724
She performed brilliantly
under very stressful circumstances.

604
00:39:50.807 --> 00:39:54.478
I appreciate your loyalty.
but you know that's not true.

605
00:40:00.776 --> 00:40:02.361
What the hell is that supposed to mean?

606
00:40:03.612 --> 00:40:06.949
Come on. Ed.
Do I really need to spell it out?

607
00:40:08.033 --> 00:40:10.077
-The whole thing with her arm--
-That wasn't her fault.

608
00:40:11.161 --> 00:40:14.748
-Well. the public thinks--
-So we change public opinion.

609
00:40:14.831 --> 00:40:17.960
Tom. I trained with Poole.
And I agree with Ed.

610
00:40:18.544 --> 00:40:19.586
So do I.

611
00:40:20.254 --> 00:40:23.882
She did an exceptional job for us
during the Apollo 24 crisis.

612
00:40:25.259 --> 00:40:26.969
And I think it's time

613
00:40:27.052 --> 00:40:29.847
for an African American woman
to command a spaceflight.

614
00:40:30.514 --> 00:40:31.849
There's no argument there.

615
00:40:31.932 --> 00:40:34.977
Hell. I'm the one that selected Poole
as an astronaut to begin with.

616
00:40:35.060 --> 00:40:36.436
So what's the problem?

617
00:40:37.479 --> 00:40:39.523
I'm gonna get a lot of blowback
from the White House.

618
00:40:41.024 --> 00:40:44.862
You need to remind them of the plaque
that we were gonna bring up on Apollo 11.

619
00:40:44.945 --> 00:40:47.865
"We came in peace for all mankind."

620
00:40:47.948 --> 00:40:49.658
Now we need to live up to that.

621
00:40:49.741 --> 00:40:52.494
And this mission.
with all its symbolic value.

622
00:40:52.578 --> 00:40:54.496
is the perfect opportunity to do so.

623
00:40:54.580 --> 00:40:56.206
I think Ed's right on this one.

624
00:40:56.999 --> 00:40:59.835
Now look. the Soviets
love to grab any opportunity

625
00:40:59.918 --> 00:41:02.588
to highlight our troubled history
with race relations.

626
00:41:02.671 --> 00:41:06.758
This will send a powerful message
about the progress that we've made.

627
00:41:09.803 --> 00:41:12.639
All right. I'll run it up the flagpole.

628
00:41:12.723 --> 00:41:14.766
Let me know if anyone
gives you any trouble on that.

629
00:41:14.850 --> 00:41:17.936
I'll call the secretary of defense.
and he'll support this.

630
00:41:19.271 --> 00:41:20.689
I got your back on this. Tom.

631
00:41:22.107 --> 00:41:23.108
[murmurs]

632
00:41:47.007 --> 00:41:50.761
T-minus five. four. three. two--

633
00:41:53.305 --> 00:41:54.473
Can I have a minute?

634
00:41:55.974 --> 00:41:57.476
You got one fucking minute.

635
00:42:00.229 --> 00:42:02.064
-What's going on?
-What are you talking about?

636
00:42:02.147 --> 00:42:05.108
I thought we were friends.
You blindsided me back there.

637
00:42:05.192 --> 00:42:07.736
Wasn't premeditated. Tom.
Just happened in the moment.

638
00:42:07.819 --> 00:42:10.989
Yeah. I guess a lot of things
happen for you in the moment lately.

639
00:42:11.073 --> 00:42:13.450
You never discussed <i>Pathfinder</i>
with me either.

640
00:42:13.534 --> 00:42:16.703
And then. bang. Gordo Stevens
is suddenly off to the moon

641
00:42:16.787 --> 00:42:18.747
after being ground bound
for nearly a decade.

642
00:42:18.830 --> 00:42:21.124
Gordo's on salary.
He's one of the best pilots we got.

643
00:42:21.208 --> 00:42:24.294
Everyone knows he's a dr--
He's got a drinking problem.

644
00:42:25.462 --> 00:42:28.841
Have you taken a good look at him lately?
The man's a train wreck waiting to happen.

645
00:42:28.924 --> 00:42:30.968
Look. he's a little bit
on the chunky side right now.

646
00:42:31.051 --> 00:42:32.594
but he'll whip himself into shape.

647
00:42:32.678 --> 00:42:34.888
He always does. He aced his proficiency--

648
00:42:34.972 --> 00:42:38.100
I just hope you're making all
these decisions for the right reasons. Ed.

649
00:42:38.559 --> 00:42:41.353
Not out of nepotism or favoritism--

650
00:42:41.436 --> 00:42:43.522
Whatever kind of ism this is.

651
00:42:53.407 --> 00:42:55.659
[alarm rings]

652
00:42:58.120 --> 00:43:00.455
["I've Got You Under My Skin" plays]

653
00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:28.233
[song continues]

654
00:43:38.118 --> 00:43:39.328
[bicycle bell rings]

655
00:43:53.926 --> 00:43:56.136
[song continues]

656
00:44:41.098 --> 00:44:43.892
[engine revs]

657
00:44:43.976 --> 00:44:45.561
[song continues]

658
00:44:56.572 --> 00:44:57.614
[revs engine]

659
00:44:57.698 --> 00:44:59.449
-[clinks]
-[engine stops]

660
00:44:59.533 --> 00:45:00.909
[song ends]

661
00:45:00.993 --> 00:45:02.119
Goddamn it!

662
00:45:02.202 --> 00:45:03.704
[steam hissing]

663
00:45:03.787 --> 00:45:04.788
Shit.

664
00:45:06.164 --> 00:45:08.876
[tapping]

665
00:45:15.048 --> 00:45:16.675
Ed did say noon. right?

666
00:45:16.758 --> 00:45:17.759
That's affirm.

667
00:45:19.678 --> 00:45:22.222
What's with the hat? You're air force.

668
00:45:23.599 --> 00:45:26.310
I. um... lost a bet.

669
00:45:27.352 --> 00:45:29.354
No shit. What was it?

670
00:45:32.107 --> 00:45:34.193
I was so drunk I. uh...

671
00:45:35.068 --> 00:45:36.153
don't remember it.

672
00:45:37.362 --> 00:45:41.074
And NASA chose you to fly right seat
in its first nuclear spacecraft.

673
00:45:45.037 --> 00:45:46.413
[door thuds]

674
00:45:46.496 --> 00:45:47.664
Sorry I'm late.

675
00:45:47.748 --> 00:45:50.042
My Vette blew a rod
on my way out to Ellington.

676
00:45:50.125 --> 00:45:52.503
How old's that car anyway? What. 40 years?

677
00:45:52.586 --> 00:45:55.255
I got it 14 years ago. while you were
still playing tennis in high school.

678
00:45:55.339 --> 00:45:57.341
I'm just glad they don't make 'em
like they used to.

679
00:45:57.925 --> 00:46:00.552
Let's get this moving.
Gotta get back to Houston.

680
00:46:00.636 --> 00:46:04.139
I want you two to supervise
the sim mods while I fly out to the Cape

681
00:46:04.223 --> 00:46:06.725
to check out
the launch control center upgrades.

682
00:46:06.808 --> 00:46:08.310
Something I wanna show you first.

683
00:46:15.609 --> 00:46:18.695
-I appreciate you doing this for me. Troy.
-My pleasure. Ms. Poole.

684
00:46:19.696 --> 00:46:22.199
Not much in here but crates and mothballs.

685
00:46:23.283 --> 00:46:24.952
What are you looking for anyway?

686
00:46:25.577 --> 00:46:27.079
I wanna say hello to my ship.

687
00:46:40.759 --> 00:46:41.844
That's your ship?

688
00:46:43.804 --> 00:46:44.888
That tin can?

689
00:46:50.227 --> 00:46:51.436
That tin can.

690
00:46:54.648 --> 00:46:55.899
[lights click]

691
00:46:55.983 --> 00:46:57.401
[Ed] I give you <i>Pathfinder.</i>

692
00:47:04.074 --> 00:47:06.076
First time I've seen her ready to go.

693
00:47:06.577 --> 00:47:09.246
She's three times as powerful
as our current shuttles.

694
00:47:09.705 --> 00:47:11.540
And when we go to Mars.

695
00:47:11.623 --> 00:47:14.835
these nuclear engines
will cut 100 days off of our trip.

696
00:47:15.460 --> 00:47:19.339
Our job will be to test her
in the harshest environment we know.

697
00:47:20.549 --> 00:47:23.093
<i>-Shake every bug out of her system.</i>
-[Dani sighs]

698
00:47:28.348 --> 00:47:32.269
Now. I chose you as my crew
because you're the best.

699
00:47:32.895 --> 00:47:34.897
Dr. Ride's been working on these engines
for years.

700
00:47:34.980 --> 00:47:37.649
and it's time you rode them into space.

701
00:47:38.275 --> 00:47:41.486
Unlike you. Captain Piscotty here
has never been on orbit.

702
00:47:41.570 --> 00:47:45.240
but I've seen him ace
six backup crew assignments.

703
00:47:46.158 --> 00:47:49.828
He seems to have a sixth sense
of what can go wrong and how to fix it.

704
00:47:50.954 --> 00:47:52.539
He's also a pretty fair pilot.

705
00:47:53.248 --> 00:47:54.750
Even though he does have red hair.

706
00:47:58.504 --> 00:48:01.924
Now. there'll be a lot of eyes on us.

707
00:48:03.550 --> 00:48:05.928
So we can afford no fuckups.

708
00:48:06.929 --> 00:48:08.931
That's why we will train our asses off.

709
00:48:10.098 --> 00:48:11.099
Roger that. skipper.

710
00:48:11.183 --> 00:48:12.601
Wouldn't have it any other way.

711
00:48:19.983 --> 00:48:21.193
[Ed] <i>Let's go make history.</i>

712
00:48:30.202 --> 00:48:33.330
<i>-...requests that you all rise...
-Oh. no.</i>

713
00:48:33.413 --> 00:48:35.290
<i>...and show respect</i>

714
00:48:35.374 --> 00:48:39.545
<i>while he sings
his nation's national anthem.</i>

715
00:48:39.628 --> 00:48:41.713
Kick your ass. you commie bastard.

716
00:48:41.797 --> 00:48:44.216
[man singing]

717
00:48:44.299 --> 00:48:46.844
Go on. keep singing
while you still got some teeth.

718
00:48:48.762 --> 00:48:50.389
[announcer 1] <i>Give me a break. Steve.</i>

719
00:48:50.472 --> 00:48:52.015
[announcer 2]
<i>Give me an umbrella. Hold it!</i>

720
00:48:52.099 --> 00:48:53.851
<i>-There it goes!
-Where is he?</i>

721
00:48:56.937 --> 00:48:58.355
[announcer 1] <i>Ladies and gentlemen.</i>

722
00:48:59.022 --> 00:49:01.567
<i>-from South Carolina...</i>
-[Marines' Hymn playing]

723
00:49:02.734 --> 00:49:05.487
<i>...Sergeant Slaughter!</i>

724
00:49:05.571 --> 00:49:06.613
Yeah!

725
00:49:10.284 --> 00:49:12.995
Slaughter's gonna kick his ass
all the way back to Siberia.

726
00:49:13.078 --> 00:49:14.913
Better watch Volkoff's right hand then.

727
00:49:15.956 --> 00:49:16.957
Last week in Shreveport.

728
00:49:17.040 --> 00:49:18.750
Volkoff whipped out
a foreign object from his trunks

729
00:49:18.834 --> 00:49:20.627
and then coldcocked Tito Santana.

730
00:49:20.961 --> 00:49:23.255
-You like wrestling?
-It's hilarious. Yeah.

731
00:49:23.839 --> 00:49:25.424
[Gordo] He's gonna kick your ass.

732
00:49:32.264 --> 00:49:34.349
Hey. Gordo. aren't you
supposed to be meeting Ed at Ellington?

733
00:49:34.433 --> 00:49:36.560
I thought you two were flying
down to the Cape together.

734
00:49:36.894 --> 00:49:39.479
Can't miss this. I'll drive fast.

735
00:49:39.563 --> 00:49:41.023
That's it.

736
00:49:41.106 --> 00:49:42.608
<i>Pathfinder</i> was amazing.

737
00:49:43.192 --> 00:49:46.236
but I about died when Sally
ribbed the admiral about his car.

738
00:49:46.737 --> 00:49:49.031
My mouth was so dry.
I couldn't say a word.

739
00:49:49.114 --> 00:49:50.908
Listen. zoomie.

740
00:49:51.909 --> 00:49:54.661
Ed Baldwin can trip over his dick
like anybody else.

741
00:49:55.245 --> 00:49:56.663
You're flying his right seat.

742
00:49:56.747 --> 00:49:59.750
so it is your job to call him out
when he fucks up.

743
00:50:00.542 --> 00:50:03.545
-If you can't do that. then--
-Jesus. Helena. Talk about a buzzkill.

744
00:50:04.087 --> 00:50:05.297
[announcer 1] <i>Watch out! Slingshot!</i>

745
00:50:05.714 --> 00:50:06.715
Hey. Ed.

746
00:50:07.341 --> 00:50:10.802
<i>Boy. now that is 313 pounds at least!</i>

747
00:50:12.095 --> 00:50:14.556
<i>Just being catapulted through the air...</i>

748
00:50:15.098 --> 00:50:16.475
<i>What a right arm!</i>

749
00:50:16.558 --> 00:50:18.310
[Gordo]
Yeah. that's it. Sarge! Pulverize him!

750
00:50:18.393 --> 00:50:20.729
-[announcer 1] <i>My word! Five rights...</i>
-Arrest his ass!

751
00:50:20.812 --> 00:50:22.397
<i>...and now the big guy flung across.
Sarge right--</i>

752
00:50:22.481 --> 00:50:24.399
Hammer him into the goddamn canvas!

753
00:50:24.483 --> 00:50:28.612
<i>And that one really rocked the Russian.
Volkoff down on a knee.</i>

754
00:50:30.989 --> 00:50:32.241
<i>The table's turning.</i>

755
00:50:37.663 --> 00:50:39.665
[indistinct voices echoing]

756
00:50:40.874 --> 00:50:43.961
[distorted] Hey. ref. you blind?
That's illegal use of bicuspids!

757
00:50:46.129 --> 00:50:47.130
Dad?

758
00:50:49.299 --> 00:50:50.300
Dad?

759
00:50:56.181 --> 00:50:57.182
You okay. Dad?

760
00:50:59.142 --> 00:51:01.270
Y-You can see those ants?

761
00:51:01.353 --> 00:51:03.021
Yeah. it's pretty hard to miss.

762
00:51:06.692 --> 00:51:10.654
-[man speaking over PA. indistinct]
-[truck reverse indicator beeping]

763
00:51:20.414 --> 00:51:21.915
You ready to go. buddy boy?

764
00:51:26.003 --> 00:51:27.004
What's wrong?

765
00:51:28.714 --> 00:51:29.882
I saw some ants.

766
00:51:32.843 --> 00:51:33.844
What?

767
00:51:34.428 --> 00:51:36.430
When? What were you doing?

768
00:51:36.513 --> 00:51:38.348
Was watching TV at the Outpost.

769
00:51:39.516 --> 00:51:41.894
And no booze. just Pepsi.

770
00:51:41.977 --> 00:51:44.396
They were just--
They were crawling everywhere. man.

771
00:51:45.606 --> 00:51:47.107
They were crawling everywhere.

772
00:51:48.066 --> 00:51:50.360
-Was anyone with you?
-Yeah. Danny was there.

773
00:51:50.444 --> 00:51:51.904
He was working.

774
00:51:53.197 --> 00:51:54.573
It was over pretty quick.

775
00:51:54.656 --> 00:51:58.202
Karen. she-- she-- she killed 'em
with some bug spray.

776
00:52:00.329 --> 00:52:02.539
What-- Wait. you mean the ants were real?

777
00:52:02.623 --> 00:52:06.710
I thought I was losing it again. Ed.
Thought I was seeing things again.

778
00:52:06.793 --> 00:52:08.253
I couldn't catch my breath.

779
00:52:08.337 --> 00:52:11.381
and I was shaking and sweating
all the way here.

780
00:52:13.342 --> 00:52:17.095
I could just feel 'em
on my hands and on my face.

781
00:52:19.556 --> 00:52:20.557
[groans]

782
00:52:20.641 --> 00:52:22.392
What if it happens up there again. Ed?

783
00:52:22.476 --> 00:52:24.811
Gordo. you're not hallucinating.

784
00:52:25.687 --> 00:52:26.897
This isn't happening.

785
00:52:28.440 --> 00:52:30.526
[panting]

786
00:52:30.609 --> 00:52:32.110
You know. my old man...

787
00:52:33.695 --> 00:52:36.240
he was the toughest son of a bitch
I ever saw.

788
00:52:37.824 --> 00:52:40.410
And the horrors he endured in that war.

789
00:52:40.953 --> 00:52:44.164
Guadalcanal. Peleliu. Okinawa.

790
00:52:46.124 --> 00:52:47.626
And those banzai charges.

791
00:52:48.919 --> 00:52:52.422
Japs coming at him.
screaming like wild animals.

792
00:52:52.506 --> 00:52:54.424
running right over
the backs of their dead.

793
00:52:54.508 --> 00:52:56.510
but he never left his machine gun.

794
00:52:57.177 --> 00:52:58.846
He just kept right on firing.

795
00:52:59.638 --> 00:53:01.723
I never saw him back down from anything.

796
00:53:07.020 --> 00:53:08.105
Till the cancer.

797
00:53:17.489 --> 00:53:21.076
I'd go and see him.
He's laying flat on his back in his bed.

798
00:53:21.159 --> 00:53:23.245
He's gasping like a fish out of water.

799
00:53:25.038 --> 00:53:28.166
Eyes big and wide. and he's so scared.

800
00:53:36.258 --> 00:53:37.593
I just couldn't take it.

801
00:53:38.635 --> 00:53:40.137
Just ran out of the room.

802
00:53:48.520 --> 00:53:49.605
I don't know.

803
00:53:51.231 --> 00:53:52.316
Maybe the...

804
00:53:54.484 --> 00:53:56.361
fear was in him all along.

805
00:53:58.572 --> 00:53:59.573
Deep down.

806
00:54:02.117 --> 00:54:03.660
He was just too weak to...

807
00:54:08.457 --> 00:54:10.167
to fight against it anymore.

808
00:54:13.545 --> 00:54:14.755
What am I gonna do. Ed?

809
00:54:14.838 --> 00:54:16.381
You can start acting like a man.

810
00:54:19.384 --> 00:54:20.886
-What?
-You heard me.

811
00:54:23.180 --> 00:54:24.681
You're a goddamn astronaut.

812
00:54:25.849 --> 00:54:30.020
You sat your ass on top of five and a half
million pounds of high explosive fuel

813
00:54:30.103 --> 00:54:31.813
and told them. "Light the fuse."

814
00:54:31.897 --> 00:54:34.900
And now you're sitting there
crying like a little fucking baby!

815
00:54:34.983 --> 00:54:38.654
"Oh. Ed. I'm so scared. I'm so weak."

816
00:54:38.737 --> 00:54:40.906
How about you grow a pair.
for Christ's sakes!

817
00:54:43.575 --> 00:54:45.077
Careful. Ed.

818
00:54:45.160 --> 00:54:47.454
Or what? El Gordo's gonna do something?

819
00:54:47.538 --> 00:54:48.872
El Gordo just might.

820
00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:52.125
-Maybe you have lost it.
-Shut up.

821
00:54:52.209 --> 00:54:54.211
-Maybe you're not Gordo Stevens anymore!
-Shut up!

822
00:54:57.673 --> 00:55:00.008
Why don't you book a flight to Florida
on Pan Am?

823
00:55:00.092 --> 00:55:01.760
I'm sure they can find you a seat.

824
00:55:22.573 --> 00:55:24.867
Niner-five-niner. niner-one-zero.

825
00:55:26.076 --> 00:55:30.080
Ed. we're beaucoup south of our route.
Fuel's gonna be a major problem.

826
00:55:30.873 --> 00:55:31.915
What's the deal?

827
00:55:31.999 --> 00:55:35.335
Just a little detour. Thought we'd see
if you got any stones left.

828
00:55:39.590 --> 00:55:42.009
[Ed]
<i>You're flying in dogfight territory. son.</i>

829
00:55:43.385 --> 00:55:46.889
You bastard.
Okay. I'm gonna kick your ass.

830
00:55:47.681 --> 00:55:48.891
Fight's on. buddy.

831
00:55:54.938 --> 00:55:58.609
<i>In the wake of Cold War tensions
that show no signs of easing.</i>

832
00:55:58.692 --> 00:56:02.863
<i>at least one person is calling
for everyone to just come together.</i>

833
00:56:02.946 --> 00:56:04.656
<i>His name. John Lennon.</i>

834
00:56:04.740 --> 00:56:06.575
<i>The famed musician and activist</i>

835
00:56:06.658 --> 00:56:09.286
<i>is reaching out
to world leaders and fans alike.</i>

836
00:56:09.369 --> 00:56:12.372
<i>promoting what he calls
a concert for peace.</i>

837
00:56:12.456 --> 00:56:15.125
<i>Hosted by Lennon. the concert
would take place in New York City</i>

838
00:56:15.209 --> 00:56:16.585
<i>sometime in the fall.</i>

839
00:56:16.668 --> 00:56:20.005
<i>No word yet from Paul. George or Ringo
as to whether they'll be joining.</i>

840
00:56:21.173 --> 00:56:22.174
<i>In other news.</i>

841
00:56:22.257 --> 00:56:25.052
<i>an absolutely stunning development
in Panama today.</i>

842
00:56:25.594 --> 00:56:28.263
<i>According to the Pentagon.
a team of Navy SEALs</i>

843
00:56:28.347 --> 00:56:30.974
<i>penetrated
the Panamanian military installation</i>

844
00:56:31.058 --> 00:56:34.811
<i>where the American soldiers were held
and rescued all four of the men.</i>

845
00:56:34.895 --> 00:56:35.896
No shit.

846
00:56:35.979 --> 00:56:39.233
<i>At least two Panamanian soldiers
were killed in the exchange of gunfire.</i>

847
00:56:39.733 --> 00:56:41.610
<i>President Torrijos denounced the action</i>

848
00:56:41.693 --> 00:56:45.155
<i>as an outrageous violation
of Panamanian sovereignty</i>

849
00:56:45.239 --> 00:56:47.658
<i>and has called upon the Soviet Union</i>

850
00:56:47.741 --> 00:56:49.493
<i>to help his country defend itself...</i>

851
00:57:03.465 --> 00:57:05.259
-Shit.
-Oh. it's-- it's okay.

852
00:57:15.561 --> 00:57:17.062
I won't tell anyone if you won't.

853
00:57:28.407 --> 00:57:32.703
Yeah. I don't want you doing this
with Kelly though. Ever. all right?

854
00:57:33.704 --> 00:57:34.830
Aye. aye. ma'am.

855
00:57:41.295 --> 00:57:45.382
-[inhaling]
-[jet engine whooshing]

856
00:57:48.969 --> 00:57:50.053
[chuckles]

857
00:57:50.137 --> 00:57:53.348
Slippery little bastard.
Ain't gonna save you though.

858
00:57:54.224 --> 00:57:55.601
Check this out. cheesedick.

859
00:58:00.731 --> 00:58:01.857
Oh. no. you don't.

860
00:58:05.777 --> 00:58:09.364
And... there you are.

861
00:58:10.532 --> 00:58:12.534
Sorry. sailor. Saw that coming.

862
00:58:17.289 --> 00:58:18.707
Time to eat your lunch.

863
00:58:18.790 --> 00:58:20.459
-[beeping]
-Pipper's on.

864
00:58:20.542 --> 00:58:24.421
-[steady tone]
-Fox Two! That's all she wrote. buddy.

865
00:58:24.505 --> 00:58:27.591
[chuckles] Ah. geez.

866
00:58:29.051 --> 00:58:31.220
We call that a clean kill.

867
00:58:31.303 --> 00:58:34.723
[Ed] We call that dumb luck. Gordo.
Let's make it two out of three.

868
00:58:34.806 --> 00:58:36.141
-[beeping]
-Whoa.

869
00:58:37.059 --> 00:58:39.770
That's not good. Warning tone.

870
00:58:39.853 --> 00:58:42.940
Ah. Jesus. Ed. you're on fire.
You got flames under your left engine.

871
00:58:43.774 --> 00:58:45.108
Aw. shit!

872
00:58:46.944 --> 00:58:48.695
<i>You better get out and walk. buddy.</i>

873
00:58:48.779 --> 00:58:50.405
More like go for a swim.

874
00:58:50.489 --> 00:58:53.075
I'll call SAR. Ed. get out of there now!

875
00:58:53.158 --> 00:58:56.453
Mayday. Mayday. Houston Center.
NASA niner-one-zero over the Gulf.

876
00:58:56.912 --> 00:58:59.706
<i>NASA niner-five-niner
is on fire and ejecting now.</i>

877
00:59:02.334 --> 00:59:06.171
[air whooshing]

878
00:59:18.934 --> 00:59:21.270
[wind whistling]

879
00:59:32.447 --> 00:59:34.867
[waves whooshing]
